travelDetails.description: Five miles of classic California beaches and communities, when it comes to getting Hermosa Beach good, the best bet is medium tides and dual swells. All spots south of Manhattan are increasingly shadowed from south/summer swell. When the surf does make it into Hermosa, the quality of waves is largely dependent on what the sand is doing.

report.body:
No afternoon report today due to the extended holiday. 

Friday Morning Report/Outlook for South LA: Fresh NW swell showing this morning, along with some more selective SW swell, as winds are  light/variable and the tide tops out at a deep 6' high at 6:45am. End result for the dawn patrol is clean surface conditions on mushy/swampy surf mainly in the knee-thigh high range at most spots, while best exposures/combo breaks north of Manhattan hit waist high. Look for overall improvement later morning after the tide backs out for a while.

Surf size holds fairly steady during the day. Just light southerly winds develop in the afternoon then ease by the evening, so conditions remain manageable all day. Tide bottoms out at a draining -0.2' low at 1:25pm, then the incoming ocean push lends a hand over the afternoon/early evening. Best bet today for most spots looks like avoiding the tide extremes.

content.title: Southern California/Northern Baja Forecast
content.body:
• Swell Trend: Modest NW bump, lingering SW swell through Fri
  • Wind: Dicey wind Thu and Fri for OC, SD better to the north
  • Tides: Deep dawn patrol highs, drained afternoon lows
  • Water Temps: SB, Ven, LA, OC: Low 60s, SD: Low-Mid 60s

Short-Term Forecast (through Friday, November 24th)

Modest to locally fun NW swell prevails through the end of the week as small SW swell holds. The most size on the NW energy will be selective, showing best for the winter stalwarts, and a deep high tide around sunrise is going to swamp out the dawn patrols with most breaks best as the tide drops through the morning. Average spots will still struggle to get to waist high, as best breaks in southern Ventura and South SD get up to chest-shoulder high on sets during most favorable tides.

Wind and Conditions:
An area of low pressure passes through the Great Basin the end of this week and sets up dicier conditions across OC and SD the next couple of days with dominant southerly winds. Todays wind looks stronger and more problematic than Friday, but the more open exposures struggle both days. Winds and conditions look much more favorable from the South Bay north the next couple of days under more easterly winds. Conditions look more favorable across the board by the weekend.

Longer Range (Saturday, November 25th and beyond)

North Pacific Overview

The round of NW swell from the end of the week will linger on Saturday morning average breaks are still mostly below waist high but winter magnets continue to pull in a few chest high sets.

A stronger, long period NW swell remains on track for later Saturday through Monday. Highly selective, long period NW swell builds in Saturday afternoon with fun to medium size range surf for good spots before sundown. This swell is from a distant but potent storm northwest of Hawaii the last couple of days. The system has outperformed model guidance so far, packing a large area of 35-45+ seas and peak readings around 50. In spite of the strength, there are some good and not-so-good things about this storm in terms of SoCal swell production. Most notably, the storm will be strongest a long way away which will limit size and consistency somewhat, and peak energy is around 300 degrees for SoCal. That leads to highly selective surf across the region.

The end result will be feast or famine type of surf on the front end of the event Saturday PM and Sunday, meaning the top/select exposed spots will be kinda pumping while less exposed breaks will be significantly smaller. Well look for chest-head high surf at breaks with decent to good exposure (Ventura, the South Bay, northernmost OC, and SD), while standouts in Southern Ventura and Southern San Diego could get into the 2-3 overhead range. Heading into Monday surf will come down at the long period focal points and come up for average breaks across SoCal as the more westerly and relatively shorter period portion of the swell moves in. Conditions look mostly favorable through the run with another Santa Ana wind event setting up for Sunday into Monday. Stay tuned, well continue to refine the details in the next couple of days.

South Pacific Overview
Nothing major is on the radar but we should see small, overlapping SW pulses from the 24th through the 29th. These pulses will come from distant storms down in the Southern Ocean that weakened as they tracked past New Zealand into the southwest Pacific. Well see some shadowing from French Polynesia that will further inhibit size and consistency. The long run of low-end swell will show best in San Diego and Orange County where waist high sets can be expected, up to chest-shoulder high at standouts. Northern LA and parts of the South Bay will see a bit of energy but overall small most breaks will likely struggle to get to waist high, while top spots should hit waist high or a touch better.

For the last day or so of November into early December, low-end SSW swell will continue to trickle in. This looks small but may be enough to help shape for the beachbreaks if we have NPAC surf, which looks likely at this point.

Tropics
Teeny tiny Tropical Depression 20-E has developed in the EPAC. The systems small size will keep it from being a swell maker for the region.
